// A decorator hugs its parens (`@policy(bounds)`, not `@policy (bounds)`) and sits on its own line
// above the decl it annotates. `@policy`'s name lexes as the `policy` keyword, but it must format
// like any other decorator (e.g. `@allow(...)`). The `policy` DECL form keeps its space (`policy (in)`)
// — distinguished by parent — so this also guards that the decl-form spacing is unchanged.
// RUN: %arche fmt %s | grep -qE "^@policy\(bounds\)$"
// RUN: %arche fmt %s | grep -qE "^clamp :: policy \(len: int, i: int\) \{$"
// RUN: %arche fmt %s | grep -qE "^@allow\(proc_no_effect\)$"
@policy(bounds)
clamp :: policy (len: int, i: int) {
  i = len;
}
@allow(proc_no_effect)
noop :: proc()() {
}
